# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carrier-pigeon-ship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/adolf-vinnen-barquentine] She was one of the five Vinnen sisters, identical ships built by Krupps around 1921–1922 for F A Vinnen of Bremen.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/adolf-vinnen-barquentine] These were the *Carl Vinnen*, *Adolf Vinnen*, *Christle Vinnen*, *Werner Vinnen* and *Sussane Vinnen*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/adolf-vinnen-barquentine] The four masted steel auxiliary, *Magdalene Vinnen* was a 3476 ton barque constructed to a separate design in the same year and in the same yard.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/adolf-vinnen-barquentine] On 9 February 1923, during her maiden voyage from Kiel Germany to Barry, Glamorgan, Wales, *Adolf Vinnen* was driven ashore at Bass Point, Cornwall, United Kingdom in a gale.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/adolf-vinnen-barquentine] The Lizard lifeboat attended the ship, Her crew of 24 was rescued by breeches buoy from the cliffs above the wreck.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/adolf-vinnen-barquentine] *Adolf Vinnen* was the last large sailing ship wrecked in the Lizard area.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/adolf-vinnen-barquentine] The wreck lies in 12 metres (39 ft) of water.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Captain **Alfred Bulltop Stormalong** was an American folk hero and the subject of numerous nautical-themed tall tales originating in Massachusetts.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was said to be a sailor and a giant, some 30 feet (9.1 m) tall; he was the master of a huge clipper ship known in various sources as either the *Courser* or the *Tuscarora*, a ship purportedly so tall that it had hinged masts to avoid catching on the Moon.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The name of Stormalong first appeared in a cycle of sea shanties that Stan Hugill, in his *Sea Shanties of the Seven Seas*, traces back to African-American folk songs of the 1830s and '40s.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Bearing names like "Mister Stormalong", "Way Stormalong John", and "Yankee John, Stormalong", these sailors' work songs generally featured praise for a deceased seaman and for his benevolent son.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The tall tales about Stormalong first appeared in the 1911 book *Here's Audacity!* by Frank Shay.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] More tales appeared in the 1933 pamphlet *Old Stormalong Yarns* by C.E.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] New England was where he was beached as a baby, already three fathoms (18 ft) tall.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] According to one telling, he outgrew Cape Cod and moved to Boston, where he signed aboard the first ship that would take him at the age of twelve.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] He had a lifelong rivalry with a Kraken, a huge sea monster from Norse myth; in fact, the Kraken escaped from him in their first encounter, causing a dejected Stormalong to abandon the sea life for life as a farmer somewhere in the Midwest.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Some sources say he had a ship so large that a stable of Arabian horses were aboard for his crew to get from one end of the ship to the other.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Among other things, the ship Alfred was best said to have drilled the course of the Panama Canal by slamming into the Panamanian coast, and to have gotten stuck in the English Channel, which required the crew to grease the ship's hull with soap.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The soap combined with the scraping of the hull against the Gray Cliffs of Dover turned them bright white.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] As Stormalong grew older, he eventually encountered the Kraken again, this time successfully drawing the beast into a whirlpool from which it never escaped.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The aged Stormalong won the race by several miles, but the stress of handling the wheel through the difficult Atlantic crossing killed him.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was buried at sea, and Davy Jones himself opened his famous locker to accept Stormalong's body.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Another ending to his life is as follows: While Stormalong was on his Caribbean adventures, he passed by Florida, seeing that there was a tremendous hurricane that tore through his ship.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Ships sailing nearby were being tossed around by the heavy waves.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong went overboard and piled as many boats as he could onto his ship.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] When the storm finally wound down, the sailors were dropped back off at Florida.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] After that, he went back on board, unfurling the sails of his ship, seeing if they could be repaired.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A great wind, the last blow of the hurricane, hit the sails, lifting Stormalong and his ship into the sky.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A third ending to his life takes advantage of the inference that, being a giant, Alfred Bulltop Stormalong was an enormous eater.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] It describes a time when his hunger was greater than usual and led him to eat so much food (one variant cites a breakfast of six sharks; it is not definitely known what other variants exist) that he suffered terminal indigestion, causing his magnificent appetite to finish him.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/ambassador-clipper] William Walker built *Ambassador* at Lavender Dry Dock in London.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/ambassador-clipper] Though considered a fast ship, *Ambassador* was said to be "very cranky and overmasted".
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/ambassador-clipper] Her first passage to the UK from Fuzhou came during the Tea Race of 1870 under Captain Duggan and took 115 days, a mediocre performance; that same year the fastest tea passage, also from Fuzhou, was made by the clipper *Lahloo* in just 98 days.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/ambassador-clipper] *Ambassador*'s fastest passage between China and England was 108 days, in 1872.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/ambassador-clipper] The wreck is now reduced to a skeletal frame.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The *Amsterdam* was a Dutch "Transom Return Ship" (Dutch: *Spiegelretourschip*) built as an East Indiaman for transport between the Dutch Republic and the settlements and strongholds of the Dutch East India Company in the East Indies.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] On an outward voyage these ships carried guns and bricks for the settlements and strongholds, and silver and golden coins to purchase Asian goods.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] On a return journey the ships carried the goods that were purchased, such as spices, fabrics, and china.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] In both directions the ships carried victuals, clothes, and tools for the sailors and soldiers on the ship.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] On an outward voyage of eight months, the ships were populated by around 240 men, and on a return journey by around 70.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The *Amsterdam* was built in the shipyard for the Amsterdam chamber of the Dutch East India Company in Amsterdam.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The maiden voyage of the *Amsterdam* was planned from the Dutch island Texel to the settlement Batavia in the East Indies.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The ship, commanded by the 33-year-old captain Willem Klump, had 203 crew, 127 soldiers, and 5 passengers.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The *Amsterdam* was laden with textiles, wine, stone ballast, cannon, paper, pens, pipes, domestic goods and 27 chests of silver guilder coins.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The ship's entire cargo would be worth several million euros in modern currency.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] On 15 November 1748 the ship made its first attempt but returned on 19 November 1748 due to an adverse wind.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The ship made a second attempt on 21 November 1748, which also failed and from which the ship returned on 6 December 1748.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The third attempt was made on 8 January 1749.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The *Amsterdam* had problems in the English Channel tacking into a strong westerly storm.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] For many days she got no further than Beachy Head near Eastbourne.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] An epidemic appeared amongst the crew and a mutiny broke out.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] Finally the rudder broke off and the ship, helpless in a storm, grounded in the mud and sand in the bay of Bulverhythe on 26 January 1749, 5 km (3.1 mi) to the west of Hastings.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] She began to sink into the mud, where much of the keel remains today, perfectly preserved.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] Some of the cargo, including silver coinage, was removed for safekeeping by local authorities.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] There was an outbreak of fighting between scavengers and British troops had to be called in to bring the situation to order.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The crew were looked after locally before being returned to Dutch soil.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] In 1969, the *Amsterdam* was discovered after being exposed by a low spring tide.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] It is the best-preserved VOC ship ever found.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] Archaeologist Peter Marsden did the first surveying of the wreck, and he advised further excavation.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The wrecksite was designated under the Protection of Wrecks Act on 5 February 1974.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The VOC Ship Amsterdam Foundation started researching the wreck, followed by major excavations in 1984, 1985 and 1986, during which huge numbers of artefacts were found.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] Although the wreck is submerged in the sand and mud of the beach (and is even visible at very low tides), much of the excavation was done by divers, for whom a small tower was constructed near the wreck.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] Additionally the wreck was surrounded by an iron girder frame.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The archeological output was so dense that new ways of researching needed to be developed, all of which were needed to understand the technological, socio-economic and cultural features of the VOC.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] Some of the finds are on show at the Shipwreck Museum in Hastings, East Sussex, UK, including one of the anchors, the other being on display as public art at St Katharine Docks in London.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The wreck is protected and diving on it or removing timbers or any artefacts is forbidden.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The ship may be visited as the timbers are exposed at very low tides in the sand just opposite the footbridge over the railway line at Bulverhythe.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] A replica of the ship was built in Iroko wood by 300 volunteers using modern tools as well as tools of the period, between 1985 and 1990 at the Zouthaven (now Piet Heinkade), Amsterdam.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] It is moored next to the Netherlands Maritime Museum, where it is open to visitors of the museum (which has now reopened after being closed for several years for renovations).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] Several decks and much of the bowsprit lie submerged in the mud and are in remarkably good condition, being naturally preserved by the mud, and much of the cargo is still aboard.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The comic book *Angst op de "Amsterdam"* of Spike and Suzy is about the *Amsterdam*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The book was published in 1985 in The Red Series of Spike and Suzy.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] In the miniature park Madurodam in The Hague is a model of the *Amsterdam* on a scale of 1:25.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] The Amsterdam Museum also has a wooden model of the ship with to the side a 'Camel' lifting mechanism.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/amsterdam-1748-ship] Shanty Punk band Skinny Lister, some of whom live in Hastings, released a single "Damn the Amsterdam" about the ship.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] An **anchor** is a device, normally made of metal, used to secure a vessel to the bed of a body of water to prevent the craft from drifting due to wind or current.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The word derives from Latin **ancora**, which itself comes from the Greek ἄγκυρα (*ankȳra*).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Anchors can either be temporary or permanent.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Permanent anchors are used in the creation of a mooring, and are rarely moved; a specialist service is normally needed to move or maintain them.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Vessels carry one or more temporary anchors, which may be of different designs and weights.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A sea anchor is a drag device, not in contact with the seabed, used to minimize drift of a vessel relative to the water.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A drogue is a drag device used to slow or help steer a vessel running before a storm in a following or overtaking sea, or when crossing a bar in a breaking sea.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Anchors achieve holding power either by "hooking" into the seabed, or weight, or a combination of the two.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The weight of the anchor chain can be more than that of the anchor and is critical to proper holding.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Permanent moorings use large masses (commonly a block or slab of concrete) resting on the seabed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Semi-permanent mooring anchors (such as mushroom anchors) and large ship's anchors derive a significant portion of their holding power from their weight, while also hooking or embedding in the bottom.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Modern anchors for smaller vessels have metal *flukes* that hook on to rocks on the bottom or bury themselves in soft seabed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The vessel is attached to the anchor by the *rode* (also called a *cable* or a *warp*).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It can be made of rope, chain or a combination of rope and chain.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The ratio of the length of rode to the water depth is known as the scope.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Holding ground is the area of sea floor that holds an anchor, and thus the attached ship or boat.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Different types of anchor are designed to hold in different types of holding ground.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Some bottom materials hold better than others; for instance, hard sand holds well, shell holds poorly.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Holding ground may be fouled with obstacles.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] An anchorage location may be chosen for its holding ground.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In poor holding ground, only the weight of an anchor and chain matters; in good holding ground, it is able to dig in, and the holding power can be significantly higher.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The basic anchoring consists of determining the location, dropping the anchor, laying out the scope, setting the hook, and assessing where the vessel ends up.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The ship seeks a location that is sufficiently protected; has suitable holding ground, enough depth at low tide and enough room for the boat to swing.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The location to drop the anchor should be approached from down wind or down current, whichever is stronger.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] As the chosen spot is approached, the vessel should be stopped or even beginning to drift back.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The anchor should initially be lowered quickly but under control until it is on the bottom (see anchor windlass).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The vessel should continue to drift back, and the cable should be veered out under control (slowly) so it is relatively straight.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Once the desired scope is laid out, the vessel should be gently forced astern, usually using the auxiliary motor but possibly by backing a sail.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A hand on the anchor line may telegraph a series of jerks and jolts, indicating the anchor is dragging, or a smooth tension indicative of digging in.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] As the anchor begins to dig in and resist backward force, the engine may be throttled up to get a thorough set.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Lowering a concentrated, heavy weight down the anchor line – rope or chain – directly in front of the bow to the seabed behaves like a heavy chain rode and lowers the angle of pull on the anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] If the weight is suspended off the seabed it acts as a spring or shock absorber to dampen the sudden actions that are normally transmitted to the anchor and can cause it to dislodge and drag.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In light conditions, a kellet reduces the swing of the vessel considerably.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In heavier conditions these effects disappear as the rode becomes straightened and the weight ineffective.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Known as an "anchor chum weight" or "angel" in the UK.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Using two anchors set approximately 45° apart, or wider angles up to 90°, from the bow is a strong mooring for facing into strong winds.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] To set anchors in this way, first one anchor is set in the normal fashion.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Then, taking in on the first cable as the boat is motored into the wind and letting slack while drifting back, a second anchor is set approximately a half-scope away from the first on a line perpendicular to the wind.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] After this second anchor is set, the scope on the first is taken up until the vessel is lying between the two anchors and the load is taken equally on each cable.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This moor also to some degree limits the range of a vessel's swing to a narrower oval.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Care should be taken that other vessels do not swing down on the boat due to the limited swing range.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] (Not to be mistaken with the *Bahamian moor*, below.) In the *bow and stern* technique, an anchor is set off each the bow and the stern, which can severely limit a vessel's swing range and also align it to steady wind, current or wave conditions.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] One method of accomplishing this moor is to set a bow anchor normally, then drop back to the limit of the bow cable (or to double the desired scope, e.g.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] 8:1 if the eventual scope should be 4:1, 10:1 if the eventual scope should be 5:1, etc.) to lower a stern anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] By taking up on the bow cable the stern anchor can be set.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] After both anchors are set, tension is taken up on both cables to limit the swing or to align the vessel.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Similar to the above, a *Bahamian moor* is used to sharply limit the swing range of a vessel, but allows it to swing to a current.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] One of the primary characteristics of this technique is the use of a swivel as follows: the first anchor is set normally, and the vessel drops back to the limit of anchor cable.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A second anchor is attached to the end of the anchor cable, and is dropped and set.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A swivel is attached to the middle of the anchor cable, and the vessel connected to that.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The vessel now swings in the middle of two anchors, which is acceptable in strong reversing currents, but a wind perpendicular to the current may break out the anchors, as they are not aligned for this load.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Also known as *tandem anchoring*, in this technique two anchors are deployed in line with each other, on the same rode.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] With the foremost anchor reducing the load on the aft-most, this technique can develop great holding power and may be appropriate in "ultimate storm" circumstances.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It does not limit swinging range, and might not be suitable in some circumstances.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] There are complications, and the technique requires careful preparation and a level of skill and experience above that required for a single anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In yachts, a kedge anchor is an anchor carried in addition to the main, or bower, anchor, and usually stowed aft.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Every yacht should carry at least two anchors – the main or *bower* anchor and a second lighter *kedge* anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It is used occasionally when it is necessary to limit the turning circle as the yacht swings when it is anchored, such as in a narrow river or a deep pool in an otherwise shallow area.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Kedge anchors are sometimes used to recover vessels that have run aground.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] For ships, a kedge may be dropped while a ship is underway, or carried out in a suitable direction by a tender or ship's boat to enable the ship to be winched off if aground or swung into a particular heading, or even to be held steady against a tidal or other stream.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Historically, it was of particular relevance to sailing warships that used them to outmaneuver opponents when the wind had dropped but might be used by any vessel in confined, shoal water to place it in a more desirable position, provided she had enough manpower.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] When a vessel is in a narrow channel or on a lee shore so that there is no room to tack the vessel in a conventional manner, an anchor attached to the lee quarter may be dropped from the lee bow.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This is deployed when the vessel is head to wind and has lost headway.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] As the vessel gathers sternway the strain on the cable pivots the vessel around what is now the weather quarter turning the vessel onto the other tack.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The anchor is then normally cut away (the ship's momentum prevents recovery without aborting the maneuver).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The anchors are usually laid in prearranged positions by an anchor tender, and the moored vessel uses its own winches to adjust position and tension.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Similar arrangements are used for some types of single buoy moorings, like the catenary anchor leg mooring (CALM) used for loading and unloading liquid cargoes.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Since all anchors that embed themselves in the bottom require the strain to be along the seabed, anchors can be broken out of the bottom by shortening the rope until the vessel is directly above the anchor; at this point the anchor chain is "up and down", in naval parlance.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] If necessary, motoring slowly around the location of the anchor also helps dislodge it.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Anchors are sometimes fitted with a trip line attached to the crown, by which they can be unhooked from underwater hazards.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The term *aweigh* describes an anchor when it is hanging on the rope and not resting on the bottom.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This is linked to the term *to weigh anchor*, meaning to lift the anchor from the sea bed, allowing the ship or boat to move.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] An anchor is described as *aweigh* when it has been broken out of the bottom and is being hauled up to be *stowed*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] *Aweigh* should not be confused with *under way*, which describes a vessel that is not *moored* to a dock or *anchored*, whether or not the vessel is moving through the water.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] *Aweigh* is also often confused with *away*, which is incorrect.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The earliest anchors were probably rocks, and many rock anchors have been found dating from at least the Bronze Age.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Pre-European Māori waka (canoes) used one or more hollowed stones, tied with flax ropes, as anchors.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Many modern moorings still rely on a large rock as the primary element of their design.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] However, using pure weight to resist the forces of a storm works well only as a permanent mooring; a large enough rock would be nearly impossible to move to a new location.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The ancient Greeks used baskets of stones, large sacks filled with sand, and wooden logs filled with lead as a weight for their ships.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Influential authors such as Apollonius Rhodius and Stephen of Byzantium also show that they may be made out of wood, Athenaeus also referring to anchors made out of metals.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Such anchors held the vessel merely by their weight and by their friction along the bottom.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Iron was afterwards introduced for the construction of anchors, and an improvement was made by forming them with teeth, or "flukes", to fasten themselves into the bottom.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This is the iconic anchor shape most familiar to non-sailors.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This form has been used since antiquity.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Roman Nemi ships of the 1st century AD used this form.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Viking Ladby ship (probably 10th century) used a fluked anchor of this type, made of iron, which would have had a wooden stock mounted perpendicular to the shank and flukes to make the flukes contact the bottom at a suitable angle to hook or penetrate.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Admiralty Pattern anchor, or simply "Admiralty", also known as a "Fisherman", consists of a central shank with a ring or shackle for attaching the rode (the rope, chain, or cable connecting the ship and the anchor).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] At the other end of the shank there are two arms, carrying the flukes, while the stock is mounted to the shackle end, at ninety degrees to the arms.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] When the anchor lands on the bottom, it generally falls over with the arms parallel to the seabed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] As a strain comes onto the rope, the stock digs into the bottom, canting the anchor until one of the flukes catches and digs into the bottom.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Admiralty Anchor is an entirely independent reinvention of a classical design, as seen in one of the Nemi ship anchors.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This basic design remained unchanged for centuries, with the most significant changes being to the overall proportions, and a move from stocks made of wood to iron stocks in the late 1830s and early 1840s.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Since one fluke always protrudes up from the set anchor, there is a great tendency of the rode to foul the anchor as the vessel swings due to wind or current shifts.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] When this happens, the anchor may be pulled out of the bottom, and in some cases may need to be hauled up to be re-set.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In the mid-19th century, numerous modifications were attempted to alleviate these problems, as well as improve holding power, including one-armed mooring anchors.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The most successful of these *patent anchors*, the Trotman Anchor, introduced a pivot at the centre of the crown where the arms join the shank, allowing the "idle" upper arm to fold against the shank.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] When deployed the lower arm may fold against the shank tilting the tip of the fluke upwards, so each fluke has a tripping palm at its base, to hook on the bottom as the folded arm drags along the seabed, which unfolds the downward oriented arm until the tip of the fluke can engage the bottom.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Handling and storage of these anchors requires special equipment and procedures.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Once the anchor is hauled up to the hawsepipe, the ring end is hoisted up to the end of a timber projecting from the bow known as the cathead.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The crown of the anchor is then hauled up with a heavy tackle until one fluke can be hooked over the rail.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This is known as "catting and fishing" the anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Before dropping the anchor, the fishing process is reversed, and the anchor is dropped from the end of the cathead.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The stockless anchor, patented in England in 1821, represented the first significant departure in anchor design in centuries.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Although their holding-power-to-weight ratio is significantly lower than admiralty pattern anchors, their ease of handling and stowage aboard large ships led to almost universal adoption.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In contrast to the elaborate stowage procedures for earlier anchors, stockless anchors are simply hauled up until they rest with the shank inside the hawsepipes, and the flukes against the hull (or inside a recess in the hull called the anchor box).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] While there are numerous variations, stockless anchors consist of a set of heavy flukes connected by a pivot or ball and socket joint to a shank.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Cast into the crown of the anchor is a set of tripping palms, projections that drag on the bottom, forcing the main flukes to dig in.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Until the mid-20th century, anchors for smaller vessels were either scaled-down versions of admiralty anchors, or simple grapnels.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] As new designs with greater holding-power-to-weight ratios were sought, a great variety of anchor designs have emerged.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Many of these designs are still under patent, and other types are best known by their original trademarked names.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A traditional design, the grapnel is merely a shank (no stock) with four or more tines, also known as a *drag*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It has a benefit in that, no matter how it reaches the bottom, one or more tines are aimed to set.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In coral, or rock, it is often able to set quickly by hooking into the structure, but may be more difficult to retrieve.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A grapnel is often quite light, and may have additional uses as a tool to recover gear lost overboard.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Its weight also makes it relatively easy to move and carry, however its shape is generally not compact and it may be awkward to stow unless a collapsing model is used.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Grapnels rarely have enough fluke area to develop much hold in sand, clay, or mud.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It is not unknown for the anchor to foul on its own rode, or to foul the tines with refuse from the bottom, preventing it from digging in.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] On the other hand, it is quite possible for this anchor to find such a good hook that, without a trip line from the crown, it is impossible to retrieve.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Francis Herreshoff, this is essentially the same pattern as an admiralty anchor, albeit with small diamond-shaped flukes or palms.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The novelty of the design lay in the means by which it could be broken down into three pieces for stowage.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In use, it still presents all the issues of the admiralty pattern anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Originally designed as a lightweight anchor for seaplanes, this design consists of two plough-like blades mounted to a shank, with a folding stock crossing through the crown of the anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Many manufacturers produce a plough-type anchor, so-named after its resemblance to an agricultural plough.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] All such anchors are copied from the original CQR (*Coastal Quick Release*, or *Clyde Quick Release*, later rebranded as 'secure' by Lewmar), a 1933 design patented in the UK by mathematician Geoffrey Ingram Taylor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Plough anchors stow conveniently in a roller at the bow, and have been popular with cruising sailors and private boaters.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Ploughs can be moderately good in all types of seafloor, though not exceptional in any.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Contrary to popular belief, the CQR's hinged shank is not to allow the anchor to turn with direction changes rather than breaking out, but actually to prevent the shank's weight from disrupting the fluke's orientation while setting.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The hinge can wear out and may trap a sailor's fingers.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Some later plough anchors have a rigid shank, such as the Lewmar's "Delta".
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A plough anchor has a fundamental flaw: like its namesake, the agricultural plough, it digs in but then tends to break out back to the surface.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Plough anchors sometimes have difficulty setting at all, and instead skip across the seafloor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] By contrast, modern efficient anchors tend to be "scoop" types that dig ever deeper.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Delta anchor was derived from the CQR.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It was patented by Philip McCarron, James Stewart, and Gordon Lyall of British marine manufacturer Simpson-Lawrence Ltd in 1992.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It was designed as an advance over the anchors used for floating systems such as oil rigs.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It retains the weighted tip of the CQR but has a much higher fluke area to weight ratio than its predecessor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The designers also eliminated the sometimes troublesome hinge.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It is a plough anchor with a rigid, arched shank.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It is described as *self-launching* because it can be dropped from a bow roller simply by paying out the rode, without manual assistance.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This is an oft copied design with the European Brake and Australian Sarca Excel being two of the more notable ones.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Although it is a plough type anchor, it sets and holds reasonably well in hard bottoms.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] American Richard Danforth invented the Danforth Anchor in the 1940s for use aboard landing craft.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It uses a stock at the crown to which two large flat triangular flukes are attached.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The stock is hinged so the flukes can orient toward the bottom (and on some designs may be adjusted for an optimal angle depending on the bottom type).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Tripping palms at the crown act to tip the flukes into the seabed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The design is a burying variety, and once well set can develop high resistance.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Its lightweight and compact flat design make it easy to retrieve and relatively easy to store; some anchor rollers and hawsepipes can accommodate a fluke-style anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A Danforth does not usually penetrate or hold in gravel or weeds.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In boulders and coral it may hold by acting as a hook.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] If there is much current, or if the vessel is moving while dropping the anchor, it may "kite" or "skate" over the bottom due to the large fluke area acting as a sail or wing.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The FOB HP anchor designed in Brittany in the 1970s is a Danforth variant designed to give increased holding through its use of rounded flukes setting at a 30° angle.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Fortress is an American aluminum alloy Danforth variant that can be disassembled for storage and it features an adjustable 32° and 45° shank/fluke angle to improve holding capability in common sea bottoms such as hard sand and soft mud.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This anchor performed well in a 1989 US Naval Sea Systems Command (NAVSEA) test and in an August 2014 holding power test that was conducted in the soft mud bottoms of the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This claw-shaped anchor was designed by Peter Bruce from Scotland in the 1970s.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Bruce gained his early reputation from the production of large-scale commercial anchors for ships and fixed installations such as oil rigs.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It was later scaled down for small boats, and copies of this popular design abound.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Bruce and its copies, known generically as "claw type anchors", have been adopted on smaller boats (partly because they stow easily on a bow roller) but they are most effective in larger sizes.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Claw anchors are quite popular on charter fleets as they have a high chance of setting on the first try in many bottoms.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] They have the reputation of not breaking out with tide or wind changes, instead slowly turning in the bottom to align with the force.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Bruce anchors can have difficulty penetrating weedy bottoms and grass.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] They offer a fairly low holding-power-to-weight ratio and generally have to be oversized to compete with newer types.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Three time circumnavigator German Rolf Kaczirek invented the Bügel Anker in the 1980s.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Kaczirek wanted an anchor that was self-righting without necessitating a ballasted tip.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Instead, he added a roll bar and switched out the plough share for a flat blade design.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] As none of the innovations of this anchor were patented, copies of it abound.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Alain Poiraud of France introduced the scoop type anchor in 1996.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Similar in design to the Bügel anchor, Poiraud's design features a concave fluke shaped like the blade of a shovel, with a shank attached parallel to the fluke, and the load applied toward the digging end.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It is designed to dig into the bottom like a shovel, and dig deeper as more pressure is applied.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The common challenge with all the scoop type anchors is that they set so well, they can be difficult to weigh.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] These are used where the vessel is permanently or semi-permanently sited, for example in the case of lightvessels or channel marker buoys.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The anchor needs to hold the vessel in all weathers, including the most severe storm, but needs to be lifted only occasionally, at most – for example, only if the vessel is to be towed into port for maintenance.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] An alternative to using an anchor under these circumstances, especially if the anchor need never be lifted at all, may be to use a pile that is driven into the seabed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Permanent anchors come in a wide range of types and have no standard form.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A slab of rock with an iron staple in it to attach a chain to would serve the purpose, as would any dense object of appropriate weight (for instance, an engine block).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Modern moorings may be anchored by augers, which look and act like oversized screws drilled into the seabed, or by barbed metal beams pounded in (or even driven in with explosives) like pilings, or by a variety of other non-mass means of getting a grip on the bottom.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] One method of building a mooring is to use three or more conventional anchors laid out with short lengths of chain attached to a swivel, so no matter which direction the vessel moves, one or more anchors are aligned to resist the force.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The mushroom anchor is suitable where the seabed is composed of silt or fine sand.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It was invented by Robert Stevenson, for use by an 82-ton converted fishing boat, *Pharos*, which was used as a lightvessel between 1807 and 1810 near to Bell Rock whilst the lighthouse was being constructed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It is shaped like an inverted mushroom, the head becoming buried in the silt.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A counterweight is often provided at the other end of the shank to lay it down before it becomes buried.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A mushroom anchor normally sinks in the silt to the point where it has displaced its own weight in bottom material, thus greatly increasing its holding power.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] These anchors are suitable only for a silt or mud bottom, since they rely upon suction and cohesion of the bottom material, which rocky or coarse sand bottoms lack.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The holding power of this anchor is at best about twice its weight until it becomes buried, when it can be as much as ten times its weight.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] They are available in sizes from about 5 kg up to several tons.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A deadweight is an anchor that relies solely on being a heavy weight.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] It is usually just a large block of concrete or stone at the end of the chain.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Its holding power is defined by its weight underwater (i.e., taking its buoyancy into account) regardless of the type of seabed, although suction can increase this if it becomes buried.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Consequently, deadweight anchors are used where mushroom anchors are unsuitable, for example in rock, gravel or coarse sand.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] An advantage of a deadweight anchor over a mushroom is that if it does drag, it continues to provide its original holding force.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The disadvantage of using deadweight anchors in conditions where a mushroom anchor could be used is that it needs to be around ten times the weight of the equivalent mushroom anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Auger anchors can be used to anchor permanent moorings, floating docks, fish farms, etc.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] These anchors, which have one or more slightly pitched self-drilling threads, must be screwed into the seabed with the use of a tool, so require access to the bottom, either at low tide or by use of a diver.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Hence they can be difficult to install in deep water without special equipment.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Weight for weight, augers have a higher holding than other permanent designs, and so can be cheap and relatively easily installed, although difficult to set in extremely soft mud.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] There is a need in the oil-and-gas industry to resist large anchoring forces when laying pipelines and for drilling vessels.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] These anchors are installed and removed using a support tug and pennant/pendant wire.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Some examples are the Stevin range supplied by Vrijhof Ankers.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Large plate anchors such as the Stevmanta are used for permanent moorings.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The elements of anchoring gear include the anchor, the cable (also called a *rode*), the method of attaching the two together, the method of attaching the cable to the ship, charts, and a method of learning the depth of the water.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Vessels may carry a number of anchors: *bower anchors* are the main anchors used by a vessel and normally carried at the bow of the vessel.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A *kedge anchor* is a light anchor used for warping an anchor, also known as *kedging*, or more commonly on yachts for mooring quickly or in benign conditions.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A *stream anchor*, which is usually heavier than a *kedge anchor*, can be used for kedging or warping in addition to temporary mooring and restraining stern movement in tidal conditions or in waters where vessel movement needs to be restricted, such as rivers and channels.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Knowing the location of potential dangers, as well as being useful in estimating the effects of weather and tide in the anchorage, is essential in choosing a good place to drop the hook.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] One can get by without referring to charts, but they are an important tool and a part of good anchoring gear, and a skilled mariner would not choose to anchor without them.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The anchor rode (or "cable" or "warp") that connects the anchor to the vessel is usually made up of chain, rope, or a combination of those.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Smaller craft might use a rope/chain combination or an all chain rode.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] All rodes should have some chain; chain is heavy but it resists abrasion from coral, sharp rocks, or shellfish beds, whereas a rope warp is susceptible to abrasion and can fail in a short time when stretched against an abrasive surface.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The weight of the chain also helps keep the direction of pull on the anchor closer to horizontal, which improves holding, and absorbs part of snubbing loads.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Where weight is not an issue, a heavier chain provides better holding by forming a catenary curve through the water and resting as much of its length on the bottom as would not be lifted by tension of the mooring load.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Any changes to the tension are accommodated by additional chain being lifted or settling on the bottom, and this absorbs shock loads until the chain is straight, at which point the full load is taken by the anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Additional dissipation of shock loads can be achieved by fitting a snubber between the chain and a bollard or cleat on deck.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This also reduces shock loads on the deck fittings, and the vessel usually lies more comfortably and quietly.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Being strong and elastic, nylon rope is the most suitable as an anchor rode.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Polyester (terylene) is stronger but less elastic than nylon.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Both materials sink, so they avoid fouling other craft in crowded anchorages and do not absorb much water.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Neither breaks down quickly in sunlight.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Elasticity helps absorb shock loading, but causes faster abrasive wear when the rope stretches over an abrasive surface, like a coral bottom or a poorly designed chock.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Polypropylene ("polyprop") is not suited to rodes because it floats and is much weaker than nylon, being barely stronger than natural fibres.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Some grades of polypropylene break down in sunlight and become hard, weak, and unpleasant to handle.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Natural fibres such as manila or hemp are still used in developing nations but absorb a lot of water, are relatively weak, and rot, although they do give good handling grip and are often relatively cheap.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Ropes that have little or no elasticity are not suitable as anchor rodes.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Elasticity is partly a function of the fibre material and partly of the rope structure.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] All anchors should have a chain of at least equal to the boat's length.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Some skippers prefer an all chain warp for greater security on coral or sharp edged rock bottoms.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The chain should be shackled to the warp through a steel eye or spliced to the chain using a chain splice.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The shackle pin should be securely wired or moused.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Either galvanized or stainless steel is suitable for eyes and shackles, galvanized steel being the stronger of the two.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Some skippers prefer to add a swivel to the rode.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] There is a school of thought that says this swivel should not be connected to the anchor itself, but be somewhere in the chain.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] However, most skippers connect the swivel directly to the anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Scope is the ratio of length of the rode to the depth of the water measured from the highest point (usually the anchor roller or bow chock) to the seabed, making allowance for the highest expected tide.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] When making this ratio large enough, one can ensure that the pull on the anchor is as horizontal as possible.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This will make it unlikely for the anchor to break out of the bottom and drag, if it was properly embedded in the seabed to begin with.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] When deploying chain, a large enough scope leads to a load that is entirely horizontal, whilst an anchor rode made only of rope will never achieve a strictly horizontal pull.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In moderate conditions, the ratio of rode to water depth should be 4:1 – where there is sufficient swing-room, a greater scope is always better.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] In rougher conditions it should be up to twice this with the extra length giving more stretch and a smaller angle to the bottom to resist the anchor breaking out.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] For example, if the water is 8 metres (26 ft) deep, and the anchor roller is 1 m (3 ft) above the water, then the 'depth' is 9 meters (~30 feet).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The amount of rode to let out in moderate conditions is thus 36 meters (120 feet).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] When using a rope rode, there is a simple way to estimate the scope: The ratio of bow height of the rode to length of rode above the water while lying back hard on the anchor is the same or less than the scope ratio.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The basis for this is simple geometry (Intercept Theorem): The ratio between two sides of a triangle stays the same regardless of the size of the triangle as long as the angles do not change.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Generally, the rode should be between 5 and 10 times the depth to the seabed, giving a scope of 5:1 or 10:1; the larger the number, the shallower the angle is between the cable and the seafloor, and the less upwards force is acting on the anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A 10:1 scope gives the greatest holding power, but also allows for much more drifting about due to the longer amount of cable paid out.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Anchoring with sufficient scope and/or heavy chain rode brings the direction of strain close to parallel with the seabed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] This is particularly important for light, modern anchors designed to bury in the bottom, where scopes of 5:1 to 7:1 are common, whereas heavy anchors and moorings can use a scope of 3:1, or less.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Some modern anchors, such as the Ultra holds with a scope of 3:1; but, unless the anchorage is crowded, a longer scope always reduces shock stresses.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] As a consequence, in deep water the scope needed will be less, whilst in very shallow water the scope must be chosen much larger to achieve the same pulling angle at the anchor shank.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] For this reason, the British Admiralty does not use a linear scope formula, but a square root formula instead.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] A couple of online calculators exist to work out the amount of chain and rope needed to achieve a (possibly nearly) horizontal pull at the anchor shank, and the associated anchor load.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Consequences of failure depend on circumstances, but may include wrecking by being driven aground on a lee shore, a particularly serious risk for sailing vessels without auxiliary propulsion when embayed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] An anchor frequently appears on the flags and coats of arms of institutions involved with the sea, as well as of port cities and seacoast regions and provinces in various countries.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] There also exists in heraldry the "Anchored Cross", or Mariner's Cross, a stylized cross in the shape of an anchor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The symbol can be used to signify 'fresh start' or 'hope'.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Mariner's Cross is also referred to as St.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Clement's Cross, in reference to the way this saint was killed (being tied to an anchor and thrown from a boat into the Black Sea in 102).
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] Anchored crosses are occasionally a feature of coats of arms in which context they are referred to by the heraldic terms *anchry* or *ancre*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anchor] The Unicode anchor (Miscellaneous Symbols) is represented by: U+2693 ⚓ ANCHOR.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ***Andrew Jackson*** was a 1,679-registered-ton medium clipper built by the firm of Irons & Grinnell in Mystic, Connecticut in 1855.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was designed for the shipping firm of J.H.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] Brower & Co. to carry cargo intended for sale to participants in the California Gold Rush.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ship was 220 feet (67 m) in length, had a beam of 41 ft., 2 in., and a draft 22 ft., 3 in.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was described as "a very handsome, well-designed ship.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] This was one of only three 89-day runs performed by square-rigged ships driving from New York City to California.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] The other two runs were both posted by *Flying Cloud*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud*'s fastest New York-to-California run had taken 89 days and 8 hours; *Andrew Jackson*'s run was, by four hours, widely acclaimed in the newspapers as the fastest in history.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some clipper ship authorities, including Howe and Matthews, assert that *Andrew Jackson* did not actually set the record described above.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] They concede, however, that this medium clipper, perhaps not naturally as fast as *Flying Cloud*, achieved a remarkable passage as the result of a combination of hard driving by the captain and favorable winds.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] However, after careful scrutiny of the logbooks, one author, Carl C.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] Cutler, concludes that a case can be made for either *Flying Cloud* or *Andrew Jackson* holding the record.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some will consider the passage from pilot-to-pilot as the appropriate indicator of fastest sailing performance around Cape Horn.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud* holds the record time for a passage anchor-to-anchor from New York to San Francisco, of 89 days 8 hours, while *Andrew Jackson'*s completed passage anchor-to-anchor may have been as long as 89 days 20 hours.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] The schooner ***Anglona*** was the first American opium clipper.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] She sailed in the Chinese coastal trade in the 1840s, and had a famous race with the schooner *Ariel* around Lintin Island.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Forbes was interested in fast schooners for clipper and coastal service in China.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] The first clipper which Forbes sent to China, the *Rose*, foundered in the July typhoon of 1841.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Forbes purchased *Anglona* at Brown & Bell's New York yard for Russell & Co. for use as a despatch boat between Hong Kong, Macao, and Whampoa.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Other American pilot boat models sent to China in the 1840s included the *Zephyr* and the *Spec*, also built on the New York model.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Shortly after Shanghai opened to foreign trade, three Boston pilot boats were sent: the 90 ton *Golden Gate*, the 90 ton *Siren*, and the 75 ton *Daniel Webster*, which served as pilot boats in the Yangtze River.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Within two weeks of purchase, *Anglona* sailed for China under Captain Turner.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] She arrived at Cape Horn in 61 days, and Java Head in 95 days.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Russell & Co put *Anglona* in service on the Canton River until the new treaty ports opened, at which time she was put in the coastal trade.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Captain Turner did not serve long, as he was knocked overboard by the mainboom during a sudden jibe, and drowned.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] In 1843, *Anglona* was under command of Capt.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Adamson; in 1844 she was under Captain Macfarlane.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] On September 20, 1841, *Anglona* left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo of rice from Macao bound for the East Coast; on Dec.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] 2, she left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo from Macao of opium or specie bound for Namoa.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Lee, the designer of the *Rose*, wanted to know why Forbes hadn't come to him for a clipper schooner instead, and got Forbes to agree to taking a half interest in one of his schooners if it could beat the *Anglona*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] The *Ariel*, a new 92-ton schooner built by Sprague & James at Medford, MA was taken out for a trial in 1841 out of Lewis Wharf in Boston Harbor, against the 30 ton schooner-yacht *Breeze*, which had been built for Forbes by Daniel C.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] The wind had freshened and was blowing in hard puffs.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] He had suggested taking in a second reef, but his companions assured him the wind would slacken as they approached the harbor.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] In stays off Sound Point Beacon, the Ariel laid down before she could get way on for a tack towards Long Island, and sank in seven fathoms of water.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] When *Ariel* was refloated, Lee agreed to reduce the rig, and cut down the masts as per Forbes’ suggestion.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] *Ariel* was then sent to China under Capt.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] Poor, making an 80-day passage to Anjer.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] The race between *Ariel* and *Anglona* was about 40 mi., from Macao Roads around Lintin and back, for stakes of $1,000 and Forbes’ agreement to take half-interest in *Ariel* if she won.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* was much stronger sailing to windward, due to the shallow draft of *Ariel,* and took the lead until rounding the island.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] At that point, *Ariel* set a large flying square sail and topsail.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* had no ballooning sails for running downwind, and was beaten by 17 minutes.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] On January 28, 1853, *Carrier Pigeon* left Boston.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The clipper was bound for San Francisco on her maiden voyage.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] As a commercial ship, she was to deliver general merchandise.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] In the mid-19th century, the Panama Canal had not yet been constructed, and thus the only way to reach the Pacific Ocean from the Atlantic Ocean was to sail around Cape Horn, an area infamous for its shipwrecks.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The prevailing winds in the vicinity of Cape Horn and south, blow from west to east around the world almost uninterrupted by land, giving rise to the "roaring forties" and the even more wild "furious fifties" and "screaming sixties".
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Despite this, *Carrier Pigeon* encountered no difficulties rounding the Cape.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] On June 6, 1853, the clipper was sighted at Santa Cruz, California.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] San Francisco is located only about seventy nautical miles (81 mi; 130 km) north of Santa Cruz.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The cool California Current offshore, enhanced by upwelling of cold sub-surface waters, often creates summer fog near the coast, and June 6, 1853, was no exception.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The captain of *Carrier Pigeon*, Azariah Doane, believed that the ship was far from shore, and so he gave the order to sail eastward toward the shore.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] In a few minutes the clipper hit the rocky bottom.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Heavy waves rocked the helpless clipper from side to side.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The hull was opened to the incoming tide.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] After seven feet (2.1 m) of cold Pacific water rushed into the ship, the captain and the crew had just a few moments to escape with their lives.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Because the ship was wrecked only 500 feet (150 m) from shore, all the members of the crew were able to reach the shore safely.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The news about the wreck reached San Francisco by the evening of June 7.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Coast Survey steamer *Active* was sent to the wreck.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Later on, sidewheel steamer *Sea Bird* joined the efforts in trying to save some cargo and whatever was left of *Carrier Pigeon*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Steamer *Sea Bird*'s salvage operations were under the command of the well-known "Bully" Waterman, formerly of *Sea Witch*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The crew of *Pigeon* was initially occupied with landing their own baggage through the surf, and wanted to remain ashore.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] However, Captain Waterman, with his characteristically forceful personality, set the listless crew members to work in the salvage operation, and kept order on the pitching decks as boxes of liquor came to light.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The cargo included cases of shoes and footwear, and although it was to the locals' advantage to drop boxes over the side whenever possible, so that they might be scavenged later for personal use, Capt.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The following morning, near daybreak, *Sea Bird* found herself in troubles of her own.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] As the wind picked up from the northwest with heavy swells, *Sea Bird'*s two anchors began to drag.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The ship broke free and started drifting towards the very same rocks that just a day before had wrecked *Carrier Pigeon*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The owner of *Sea Bird*, Captain John T.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Wright, had detailed knowledge of the area, and was able to maneuver his ship so that it beached a few miles south, on the sandy shore of Point Año Nuevo.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] This saved *Sea Bird* from being wrecked, and she was refloated a few months later, in October.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] One more ship, *Goliah*, was sent to help out to salvage as much merchandise as possible from the wreck.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] *Goliah* first checked on the safety of *Sea Bird* before coming to *Carrier Pigeon*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] *Goliah* was able to transport both the crew of *Carrier Pigeon* and 1,200 packages of her merchandise north to San Francisco.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The salvage operations continued for a few more weeks, but by July, *Carrier Pigeon* was breaking apart.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Both wrecks appear to have left an impression on this sparsely populated stretch of the San Mateo County coastline.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Waterman's efforts, several local stories remain regarding the disposal of the cargoes of *Carrier Pigeon* and *Sea Bird*.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] According to a guidebook published by the California Coastal Commission, the residents of Pescadero recovered a large quantity of white paint from *Pigeon* which they "used liberally on all the town's buildings", and then maintained the tradition of painting their houses white.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] However, other sources credit the 1896 wreck of the steamer *Columbia* as the source of the white paint.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] An article in the *Wells Fargo Messenger* states that a stagecoach salvaged from *Carrier Pigeon* was laboriously hoisted up the cliffs onto the road, and put into service within a week.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] The coach, built in Concord, New Hampshire, carried passengers and freight on the Pescadero road for the Wells Fargo Company for forty years, and, in 1914, was listed among the company's prized possessions.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Another tale relates that an Irishman named John Daly, who was employed driving pigs from Santa Cruz to a Pescadero ranch, discovered some lumps of coal from *Sea Bird*'s cargo on the beach at Año Nuevo.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Daly endeavored to parlay his discovery into money which he might spend on whiskey.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Since coal deposits had been rumored to exist in the area, Mr.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Daly proceeded with his lumps of coal to Santa Cruz, announcing to Captain Brannan and three others that he'd discovered a coal mine at Gazos Creek.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] After collecting his monetary reward, he led the four men up Gazos Creek in search of the alleged coal outcropping, with the intention of escaping and leaving his benefactors behind empty-handed.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] However, Captain Brannan, who was armed, managed to capture Daly and extract a confession.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] Daly was administered a whipping on the spot and later fled the area.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] A few years later, in 1871, a lighthouse was built on a point near where the wreck occurred.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] To commemorate *Carrier Pigeon*, the structure was named Pigeon Point Lighthouse.
[src:carrier-pigeon-ship/carrier-pigeon-ship] This lighthouse is still an active Coast Guard aid to navigation in the area.
